Hi there,

I'm not really sure if _.transform() is correctly categorized as a "object" function. In my understanding, if it were truly an "object" only function, then transforming an Array should not work as it does (which is great btw):

See e.g.:

```
var myArr = [2, 3, 4];
myArr.test = 5;

_.transform(myArr, function(result, n) {
  result.push(n *= n);
});
// [4, 9, 16] // 25 missing here!

_.forOwn(myArr, function(value, key) { console.log(key); })
// 0
// 1
// 2
// test

```

As one can see, _.transform() "correctly" iterates `myArr` as an Array. But if _.transform() was object only, then it should have iterated over myArr similiar to _.forOwn(), shouldn't it?
### Conclusion

Shouldn't _.transform() rather be categorized as a 'collection' function?

lodash is only an [`iterate`](https://hackage.haskell.org/package/base-4.8.1.0/docs/Prelude.html#v:iterate) away from supporting an [elegant implementation](http://neilmitchell.blogspot.com/2012/01/pascals-triangle-in-haskell.html) of [Pascal's Triangle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pascal's_triangle) (which, apparently, is a [common interview question](https://www.reddit.com/r/javascript/comments/3rb88w/ten_questions_ive_been_asked_most_more_than_once/)):

``` javascript
import _ from 'lodash';

function nextRow (row) {
    return _.zipWith([ 0, ...row ], [ ...row, 0 ], _.add);
}

function pascal (rows) {
    return (rows === 0) ? [] : _.iterate(rows, [ 1 ], nextRow);
}  

let rows = parseInt(process.argv[2]) || 6;

console.log(pascal(rows));
```

It's useful for other things as well, of course. It encapsulates the concept of generating a list by repeatedly applying a function to the previous value in the same way that `reduce` encapsulates the concept of reducing a list by repeatedly applying a function to the (current and) next value.

Happy to submit a PR if there's any interest.

